docs.abstract: After splitting from Universal, Brian Grazer and Ron Howard, who started Imagine Entertainment in 1986, find themselves making content for a host of streaming services.
docs.snippet: After splitting from Universal, Brian Grazer and Ron Howard, who started Imagine Entertainment in 1986, find themselves making content for a host of streaming services.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. — “So this is a blow gun,” Brian Grazer said during an interview in his office. “It shoots a very sharp dart.”

headline.main: Ron Howard and Brian Grazer Want to Be the Center of the Streaming Era

docs.abstract: Unemployment is low and growth is solid, but the president’s 2020 rivals are challenging the Trump economic record on several fronts.
docs.snippet: Unemployment is low and growth is solid, but the president’s 2020 rivals are challenging the Trump economic record on several fronts.
docs.lead_paragraph: It took more than 90 minutes for the moderators of the Democratic presidential primary debate on Wednesday night to turn to the economy, which polls show is a top issue on voters’ minds and is one of President Trump’s strengths as he seeks re-election.

headline.main: How Democrats Will Attack Trump on the Economy
headline.print_headline: Trade Wars and Taxes: Where Rivals May Hit Trump on the Economy

byline.original: By Jim Tankersley and Ben Casselman

docs.abstract: As part of a broader evolution, and as it moves to stave off a possible slowdown, the Federal Reserve is focusing on transparency, inclusiveness and a greater responsiveness to ordinary people.
docs.snippet: As part of a broader evolution, and as it moves to stave off a possible slowdown, the Federal Reserve is focusing on transparency, inclusiveness and a greater responsiveness to ordinary people.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Federal Reserve’s decision this week to cut rates for the first time in more than a decade was driven, in part, by a recognition that policymakers have a role to play in the fate of American workers.

headline.main: Pride Flags and Rate Cuts: Fed Loosens Up to Connect With Average Workers

docs.abstract: Wall Street’s slide continued as a clash between the world’s biggest economies cast a chill on markets.
docs.snippet: Wall Street’s slide continued as a clash between the world’s biggest economies cast a chill on markets.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stocks suffered their worst week of the year as jitters over trade returned to the financial markets, and investors worried that the Federal Reserve might not be as supportive of them as earlier hoped.

headline.main: Stocks Have Worst Weekly Drop of 2019 as Trade War Rattles Investors
headline.print_headline: More Jobs, Lower Rates and Still a Bad Week

docs.abstract: Employees at Deutsche Bank reported potentially illicit transactions to a federal regulator. Mr. Epstein, who is charged with sex trafficking, had dozens of accounts at the bank.
docs.snippet: Employees at Deutsche Bank reported potentially illicit transactions to a federal regulator. Mr. Epstein, who is charged with sex trafficking, had dozens of accounts at the bank.
docs.lead_paragraph: As Deutsche Bank officials this year scrambled to extricate themselves from a yearslong relationship with Jeffrey Epstein, the wealthy financier charged this month with sex trafficking, they uncovered suspicious transactions in which Mr. Epstein had moved money out of the United States.

headline.main: Jeffrey Epstein Moved Money Overseas in Transactions His Bank Flagged to U.S.

byline.original: By David Enrich and Jo Becker

docs.abstract: Asian markets ended lower, but shares on Wall Street and in European markets rose after President Trump and Beijing officials publicly discussed potentially restarting stalled talks.
docs.snippet: Asian markets ended lower, but shares on Wall Street and in European markets rose after President Trump and Beijing officials publicly discussed potentially restarting stalled talks.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stocks climbed in the United States on Monday after President Trump ratcheted down the tension with China, calling President Xi Jinping a “great leader” and indicating that Chinese officials had reached out to resume talks to settle the trade dispute that has unnerved investors.

headline.main: Global Stocks Uneven Amid U.S.-China Trade War Tensions
headline.print_headline: Markets in Asia Unnerved By Vows to Ramp Up Tariffs

docs.abstract: Mr. O’Donnell said his reporting hadn’t gone through MSNBC’s “rigorous verification and standards process.” The statement was likely to provide fuel for President Trump’s attacks on the media.
docs.snippet: Mr. O’Donnell said his reporting hadn’t gone through MSNBC’s “rigorous verification and standards process.” The statement was likely to provide fuel for President Trump’s attacks on the media.
docs.lead_paragraph: The MSNBC host Lawrence O’Donnell retracted a story he reported on Tuesday night that claimed President Trump had made a financial arrangement with so-called Russian oligarchs.

headline.main: Lawrence O’Donnell Retracts Claim of Russians’ Role in Trump Loans
headline.print_headline: MSNBC Host Retracts Report Asserting Russians Had Role in Trump Loans

docs.abstract: Atalaya Capital Management agreed to pay restitution to more than 100 New York residents for its financial support of Vision Property Management.
docs.snippet: Atalaya Capital Management agreed to pay restitution to more than 100 New York residents for its financial support of Vision Property Management.
docs.lead_paragraph: New York regulators have reached a settlement worth up to $2.7 million with a hedge fund that provided financing and assistance to a large rent-to-own home firm accused of engaging in predatory business practices.

headline.main: Hedge Fund Reaches Potential $2.7 Million Settlement Over Rent-to-Own Home Financing
headline.print_headline: $2.7 Million Settlement Is Reached in Rent-to-Own Case

docs.abstract: A split between larger and smaller companies reflects at least tactical differences over the best course for producers in an age of climate concerns.
docs.snippet: A split between larger and smaller companies reflects at least tactical differences over the best course for producers in an age of climate concerns.
docs.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — Oil and gas producers might have been expected to welcome a decision to loosen regulations affecting their business. But their reaction to the Trump administration’s move to roll back methane-emissions rules revealed at least tactical divisions on climate policy.

headline.main: Trump’s Methane Rule Rollback Divides Oil and Gas Industry
headline.print_headline: Rollback of Methane Rules Splits Oil and Gas Industry
